import React from 'react';

function Four() {
    return (
        <div className="blog-post">
            <h1>AI-Native Employees and Computer Science Educational Changes</h1>
            <small>02-16-2026</small>
            <p>
                This week in my AI class, we have a special guest visit on Tuesday. His name is <a href='https://www.linkedin.com/in/jefflarkin/' target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Jeff Larkin</a> and he's the director of high-performance computing at NVIDIA. In preparation for his presentation, we've been provided with two sources to look into. It was very interesting to read Elena Verna's article about <a href='https://www.elenaverna.com/p/the-rise-of-the-ai-native-employee' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'> The Rise of the AI-native Employee</a> and listen to part three of<a href='https://podwise.ai/dashboard/episodes/6197400' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>Joe Rogan's interview with Jensen Huang</a>, CEO of NVIDIA. After reading and listening, I'll be playing the role of a computer science educator to share my thoughts on how the curriculum should change.
            </p>
            <br />
            <h2>How Would I Change Computer Science Curriculum?</h2>
            <p>
                As of now, the CS curriculum is largely based on the fundamentals of coding, and how to equip students with those ideas, making them effective problem solvers. Foundational classes such as sata structures & algorithms, discrete math and systems level programming are still very important, despite the growth of AI. The aspect of current education that I disagree with is the application of foudnational principles. As educators, we're tasked with producing graduates who are prepared for the industry. In the real world, employees use AI to help them complete tasks at a much faster rate, while employing smaller teams. 
            </p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default Four;
